Vice President Joe Biden is embarking on a nine-day trip to China, Mongolia, and Japan. The purpose of the trip is to discuss a wide range of bilateral, regional, and international issues with key leaders in each country. In China, Biden will meet with Vice President Xi Jinping, President Hu Jintao, and Premier Wen Jiabao. He will also visit the city of Chengdu and deliver a speech on U.S.-China relations at Sichuan University. In Mongolia, Biden will express support for the country's democratic development and growing economic ties. In Japan, he will show steadfast U.S. support following the recent earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear emergency. Biden will thank U.S. personnel for their assistance in responding to the disaster and highlight Japan's resilience during the recovery process. The trip will conclude in Kaneohe, Hawaii, where Biden will deliver remarks at Marine Corps Base Hawaii, Kaneohe Bay.